    <prp:abstract>In this proposal, we propose to observe HCN(J=4-3) emission line on Neptune's stratosphere (1)to constrain its origin obtaining the spatial distribution of HCN and (2)to illustrate the stratospheric wind velocity map. As the origin of Neptune's stratospheric volatiles, such as HCN, upward convection is one of the possible candidate. Such upward convection makes a biased spatial distribution of HCN. Spatially-resolved observation can determine whether such the convection is the origin of stratospheric HCN or not. In addition, spatially-resolved observation can obtain the stratospheric wind map which has not obtained yet. We already performed a preliminary analysis using ALMA archive and detected the suspicious biased distribution and succeeded to detect the day to night stratospheric wind. For the further understanding of both phenomena, spatially-resolved observation is a crucial tool because our preliminary analysis could resolve Neptune's 2.2" disk with only 0.5" beam, not sufficient for the spatially-resolved observation. In this proposal, we can investigate two kind of scientific importance simultaneously by the short(~2 hours) observation time. </prp:abstract>
